<table width="97%" border="0" align="center"><tr><td style="font-weight: bold; font-size: large;">The End of a Legend</td></tr><tr><td>By Jason 'Virgil' Smith</td></tr><tr><td style="font-size: xx-small;">March 22, 2001</td></tr><tr><td>Well, as you may have heard, the last bastion of a legend is finally gone. With the cancellation of the game once known as <a href=http://origin.xrgaming.net>Ultima Online 2</a>, one of the most cherished names in gaming is finally beginning it’s faltering descent into the grave. At this point, you might think this is the beginning of a rant about the cancellation – it’s not. It’s a highlight of the death of a once-great company called Origin.<br>
<br>
Doomsayer? Perhaps, but not nearly as much as one would think. <a href=http://www.origin.ea.com>Origin Systems</a> in their prime produced amazing products – they took us into the world of Britannia, a world where there was virtue and evil, and yet they were sometimes the same thing. And the universe of Privateer, to battle off the Kilrathi menace. Crusader, Wing Commander, System Shock – games that marked their heyday as a giant, where the Origin label was a sign of quality, passion for excellence, and most of all a box containing a game to captivate our hearts and tickle the imagination.<br>
<br>
But look at them now – Their flagship game is now over three years old, no matter how many facelifts you get, you can’t remove all the wrinkles. Privateer Online, design headed by <a href= http://www.legendmud.org/raph/>Raph Koster</a>, was cancelled as it neared completion. Reason? To remove competition towards another EA title, <a href=http://www.earthandbeyond.com>Earth and Beyond</a>. Yes, they cancelled a guaranteed hit, just the Privateer label and a mediocre game is a guaranteed hit, to replace it with a game with no legacy, no history, and… well, no fans.<br>
<br>
Stepping back further, you can trace the mishaps. Ultima Online was torn to shreds by the waiting public as the systems couldn’t handle the onslaught. A recovery was managed, and the game slowly climbed up into the limelight where it reigned supreme, while other companies took note. As each competitive product was released, a new expansion for UO was shoved out to the shelves. Of course, every expansion release was rushed out before it’s time, had critical bugs and failures, and in the more recent cases have even been sent out without the actual product being finished. A new client is set for shelves soon, it’s already called ‘gold’ and on the presses, though it’s unstable, and rather bad looking. <a href= http://www.gamecenter.com/Reviews/Item/0,6,0-3496,00.html >Ultima IX</a> is almost a joke in the gaming realm – not quite as much as Daikatana, but it’s nearly up there. A game that was rushed out so quickly that they forgot to code in the ‘working’ part, though it had a pretty box.<br>
<br>
What was cancelled? Origin Systems was cancelled. Ultima Online has a life ahead of it yet, but not as a revolutionary game. It will be <a href=http://www.ea.com>EA.com</a>’s money faucet, pumping in the millions to supply their (until recently) bloated system, trying to keep them in the black until something new can take its place. It won’t last forever – it’s drained about all it can from the US market, and even the Asian one can’t last (though that’s the apparent dream of EA, milk the Asian market dry with a program that takes minimal upkeep). UO will hang on for a few more years, then collapse into nothingness, taking the name of OSI with it. They have no other games running or in development, no staff to develop new ones – Origin Systems has been cancelled.<br>
<br>
Even were they to attempt to get back into the market, look what they’ve lost. For the second time, they’ve lost a team full of the most talented designers in the industry. They took years of their lives building the first online game of this scale designed with fiction and extensibility in mind, and cancelled it after spending over a year building a fanbase. The fans feel betrayed yet again, and more confidence has been lost – for many, this is the last straw, and they’ve effectively killed off the Ultima brand in a glorious manner. How many times can one do this and still survive in the market? Well, with EA, they can do it as long as they want, because they can afford the losses.<br>
<br>
As a child I had once dreamed of working at Origin. Where they once created worlds. Over time, that thought slipped away and vanished, with the slow decay of the worlds they created, the parting of visionary Richard Garriott, and the subsequent losses of quality personnel and products. If I were offered a position tomorrow, let’s just say I’d still be at this desk in a month, and not regretting a thing. The death of dreams and end of a legend.<br>
<br>
R.I.P Origin Systems, 1983 - 2003</td></tr></table><!-- banner2 code --></td>
	</tr>
